  "footnotes": [
    "Srivijaya (c.650–1025): a Malay Buddhist maritime empire centered in Palembang, Sumatra; it controlled the Strait of Malacca and dominated Southeast Asian sea trade for centuries; Chinese pilgrim Yijing studied there in 671; Chola naval raids from India in 1025 fatally weakened it, fragmenting Sumatran power",
    "Majapahit Empire (1293–c.1527): the greatest pre-Islamic Indonesian state, centered in East Java; under Prime Minister Gajah Mada and King Hayam Wuruk, it claimed suzerainty over most of the Indonesian archipelago, the Malay Peninsula, and parts of the Philippines; the Nagarakretagama (1365) describes its vassal network; its decline coincided with the rise of Islamic coastal sultanates",
    "Mataram–Medang kingdom (c.716–1006): the Central Javanese kingdom that produced Borobudur (Buddhist, Sailendra dynasty) and Prambanan (Hindu, Sanjaya dynasty) — two of the greatest monuments in Southeast Asia; the kingdom later shifted to East Java after volcanic eruptions and political instability",
    "Samudra Pasai (c.1267–1521): the first Islamic sultanate in Southeast Asia, located in northern Sumatra; it became the model for Islamization across the Malay world; Marco Polo visited in 1292 and noted the Muslim population; its role was later taken over by the Malacca and Aceh sultanates",
    "VOC — Dutch East India Company (1602–1799): the world's first multinational corporation and joint-stock company; headquartered in Batavia (Jakarta), it monopolized the spice trade (cloves, nutmeg, pepper) through force, establishing control over Maluku, Java, and eventually most of the archipelago; it went bankrupt in 1799 and its possessions became the Dutch East Indies",
    "Aceh War (1873–1914): one of the longest colonial wars in history; the Acehnese sultanate fiercely resisted Dutch conquest; the war killed over 100,000 Acehnese and established Dutch control over all of Sumatra; Acehnese resistance identity persists — the Free Aceh Movement fought Jakarta until the 2005 peace agreement",
    "Indonesian National Revolution (1945–1949): Sukarno and Hatta proclaimed independence on 17 August 1945; the Dutch attempted to reassert control through two 'Police Actions' (1947, 1948); international pressure (especially from the US and UN) forced Dutch recognition of sovereignty on 27 December 1949; the revolution is Indonesia's founding narrative"
  ]
